    <h1>Spiffy Subaru</h1>
    <h2>Four bodykit parts and up&#xAD;dated equip&#xAD;ment gear add to the al&#xAD;ready strong al&#xAD;lure of the lat&#xAD;est Subaru XV GT edi&#xAD;tion</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200725/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-25"><time>2020-07-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Toh Yong Chuan to&#xAD;hyc@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>At the Sin­ga­pore Mo­tor­show in Jan­uary, Subaru’s lo­cal dealer Mo­tor Im­age raised eye­brows by un­veil­ing its “Forester Ul­ti­mate Cus­tomised Kit Spe­cial” edi­tion. A brouhaha en­sued over its acro­nym.</p>
    <p>Thank­fully, the Subaru XV GT edi­tion here is not as con­tro­ver­sial.</p>
    <p>“GT” in mo­tor­ing typ­i­cally means grand tourer, a type of car built for com­fort­able long-dis­tance high­speed driv­ing.</p>
    <p>But Mo­tor Im­age says the GT in the XV is not short for any­thing, even if it matches the ini­tials of its boss’ name, Mr Glenn Tan.</p>
    <p>The test-car is me­chan­i­cally iden­ti­cal to the vari­ant re­viewed by The Straits Times in 2018.</p>
    <p>The changes are vis­ual and in the equip­ment list.</p>
    <p>The GT edi­tion adds four bodykit parts to the car: a front bumper lip ex­ten­sion, side skirts, a rear bumper ex­ten­sion and a roof spoiler.</p>
    <p>It also gets new 18-inch rims with a de­sign that looks like five flower petals. The at­ten­tion to de­tail is im­pres­sive: The rims have match­ing caps with the let­ters GT in place of the Subaru logo.</p>
    <p>These add-ons do not boost the car’s per­for­mance, but they give it a sportier look.</p>
    <p>In­side, the leather seats get a new de­sign. An eight-inch touch­screen in­fo­tain­ment dis­play is now com­pat­i­ble with Ap­ple CarPlay and An­droid Auto and fea­tures a 360-de­gree cam­era that is not com­mon in cars in the XV’s price range.</p>
    <p>Af­ter a one-day, 136km test-drive, I won­dered if the up­grades were even nec­es­sary. The XV is an ap­peal­ing cross­over to be­gin with.</p>
    <p>With al­most every other car be­ing tur­bocharged these days, the XV – with its creamy, high-revving 2-litre nat­u­rally as­pi­rated en­gine – is re­fresh­ing.</p>
    <p>The car shines in the ride and han­dling de­part­ments too.</p>
    <p>It rained dur­ing most of my drive and the XV’s four-wheel driv­e­train pro­vided con­fi­dence and sure­foot­ed­ness, es­pe­cially at the curvy bends in the Neo Tiew and Mount Faber ar­eas.</p>
    <p>In terms of equip­ment, the “non-GT” XV is not want­ing ei­ther. It comes with Subaru’s cam­er­abased Eye­Sight driv­ing-aid sys­tem, which is said to help drivers avoid col­li­sions and keep in lane.</p>
    <p>The XV is a proper off-roader with as­sisted hill de­scent and an off-road driv­ing mode.</p>
    <p>It looks rugged with un­painted fen­ders and roof rails, and the new bodykit makes the car look sportier and widens its ap­peal.</p>
    <p>Its 360-de­gree cam­era may not be nec­es­sary for a 4,465mm-long car (merely 40mm longer than the Toy­ota Vios sub­com­pact), but it turned out to be use­ful when I had to make a five-point turn out of a dead-end road in Lim Chu Kang.</p>
    <p>The XV av­er­aged about 8.5 litres/100km over the test­drive – not too far off the of­fi­cial fig­ure of 7 litres/100km.</p>
    <p>Mo­tor Im­age is of­fer­ing a “non</p>
    <p>GT” ver­sion of the XV with­out the bodykit for $2,588 less.</p>
    <p>But be it the GT ver­sion or not, the XV is well-equipped, easy to live with and ap­peal­ing to keen drivers.</p>
    <p>The vis­ual and equip­ment up­grades are the ic­ing on an al­ready de­lec­ta­ble cake.</p>

